ENTRY       EC 3.2.1.156                Enzyme
NAME        oligosaccharide reducing-end xylanase;
            Rex;
            reducing end xylose-releasing exo-oligoxylanase
CLASS       Hydrolases;
            Glycosylases;
            Glycosidases, i.e. enzymes that hydrolyse O- and S-glycosyl compounds
SYSNAME     beta-D-xylopyranosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-xylopyranose reducing-end xylanase
REACTION    Hydrolysis of (1->4)-beta-D-xylose residues from the reducing end of oligosaccharides
COMMENT     The enzyme, originally isolated from the bacterium Bacillus halodurans C-125, releases the xylose unit at the reducing end of oligosaccharides ending with the structure beta-D-xylopyranosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-xylopyranosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-xylopyranose, leaving the new reducing end in the alpha configuration. It is specific for the beta anomers of xylooligosaccharides whose degree of polymerization is equal to or greater than 3.
            The penultimate residue must be beta-D-xylopyranose, but replacing either of the flanking residues with glucose merely slows the rate greatly.
